m international mechanisms, as well as climate fnance allocated through public expenditure and climate fnance that comes from private sources. Colombia is also currently the only country that is developing the \u201cmap of investments\u201d, which is the public site where all the information about fnancial fows from public investments will be reported. This information will feed the MRV on climate fnance including future Natcomm and BUR reports. The system is in construction and will be launched in 2017. The Philippines has also made progress on the establishment of the National Integrated Climate Change Database Information and Exchange System (NICCDIES), which functions as a domestic Monitoring, Reporting and Verifcation (MRV) system. It is more developed for mitigation, but currently they are expanding it to cover adaptation actions, including means of implementation (CCC, interview). 5.6 Overall Assessment of climate fnance in reporting tools As it was identifed in previous sections, the reporting on climate fnance and particularly fnance for adaptation is very recent for all case study countries. In the National Communications, climate fnance in general, was not included in the frst ones. Only in recent versions of the NatComms is climate fnance referred to, but the information is not clear enough in terms of the actual costs due to loss and damage, future fnancing needs, and/or VI. REPORTING OF CLIMATE FINANCE IN SELECTED COUNTRIES A Review of Domestic Data Sources for Climate Finance Flows in Recipient Countries 49 national and international resources spent or received to deal with climate change in the countries. Where the reference to climate fnance was included, the reports mainly identify the fnancing needs for the implementation of mitigation actions. Information on fnance for adaptation is much less developed. In the second communications, two countries (Colombia and Nepal) clearly mentioned the need of fnance for adaptation, but without including fgures. The others, included adaptation actions to be implemented, but did not mention the specifc need for fnance. The NAPAs of Zambia and Nepal included the amount of resources needed to implement the proposed projects/programs. In the NDCs, only Zambia defned a fgure for fnancing the adaptation component. In country interviews identifed the lack of information on climate projections and scenarios at the national level as a barrier to identifying the fnancing needs for adaptation. If the future impacts of climate change at the country and sub-national level are unknown, is difcult to estimate the costs of potential damages due to climate change and the needs for adaptation. Nevertheless in the interviews ofcers indicated a willingness to include climate fnance information in future NatComm and other reporting systems and suggested that methodologies to guide such eforts is needed. Table 17 below gives an assessment of the current climate fnance reporting tools in use across the selected countries. VI. REPORTING OF CLIMATE FINANCE IN SELECTED COUNTRIES 50 Table 17 Assessment of climate fnance in reporting tools Document Assessment Climate - Adaptation policies and plans General reporting schemes Climate fnance reporting \u2022 \ufffdost of the countries have developed a framework of policies to face climate change. Only three have climate change laws and two of them (Colombia and \ufffdenya) have developed its National Adaptation Plans. \u2022 Policies in place usually stress on the vulnerability of the countries and identify climate-related actions, but normally no information about the costs for the implementation of these actions is given. The National Communications and National Adaptation Plans should provide more information on costing for implementation of the climate actions, in terms of allocation and e\ufffdpenses respectively. Some of the Plans analy\ufffded presented estimates of the implementation of the activities they included. \ufffdhen figures are included, there is not clarity on how the estimations were made. \u2022 All si\ufffd countries have only presented two national communications and are in the preparation of the third one. \u2022 Only Colombia has complied with the re\ufffduirement of the \ufffdUR. \u2022 All si\ufffd countries presented their NDCs.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1d8ca7af-5b1c-4729-8841-c4be0384178c": {"__data__": {"id_": "1d8ca7af-5b1c-4729-8841-c4be0384178c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/review-domestic-data-sources-climate-finance-flows-recipient-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Review of Domestic Data Sources for Climate Finance Flows in Recipient Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/review-domestic-data-sources-climate-finance-flows-recipient-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b298719dca8cf2808f158f6046c064a4ad8d0c198f0d899c5562288ef6272ed5"}, "2": {"node_id": "6b419a36-c9bf-4fd1-87ab-c77d398c73dc", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/review-domestic-data-sources-climate-finance-flows-recipient-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8c9cb8edde2099ee25997f30495910b3af0fdded51a955448abf390610707a89"}}, "hash": "de29c31a919a6498a3222452fe51ced35b38730100b381322ec32363ce084aa5", "text": "\u2022 All si\ufffd countries presented their NDCs. \