 Central to Local Government 1 1 2 2 2 2 2 2 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 3 4 4 4 4 Enabling Environment for Cities and Local Government in Asia Pacific 55 Two South Asian countries, Pakistan and Afghanistan scored 1, indicating their resources are often not transferred, or are transferred erratically and irregularly. The unpredictability of the transfer systems in Pakistan has a trickle- down impact to other criteria and the county\u2019s overall CEE rating. The delay in transfer of funds is a common issue amongst local governments, with many unable to continue with capital investment programmes because agreed flows of funds between central and local government are erratic. Unpredictability in the timing of funds transfers makes difficult, not only the timely construction of physical infrastructure and services provided by enabling environments, but it also increases uncertainty, especially if local governments are seeking to engage in public-private partnerships. Poor vertical fiscal imbalances and transfers are a very significant constraint to effective local government throughout the region. Performance of Sub-region In terms of financial transfer from central to local governments, sub-region wise, reforms are needed in some countries in South Asia and Southeast Asia to improve reliance on the flow of funds under notional vertical fiscal resource sharing arrangements with local government to improve their performance in the delivery of essential legal and other local enabling environments services. e. Criteria 5: Local Governments\u2019 Own Revenues Criteria 5 indicates the empowerment of the local bodies in terms of determining local taxes, the introduction of local levies and taxes, independence to explore financial markets, among other. This is the weakest indicator of enabling environment performance. The Graph (See Figure 4.7) shows the performance of this indicator for the 28 countries of the region. Performance of Countries New Zealand and Solomon Islands are the only countries to score four points. have total independence to determine tax bases, rates and fees, and to collect the tax revenues. Local governments are permitted to raise capital in financial markets, and sub-sovereign lending is allowed. Many New Zealand local governments have international AA+ credit ratings because they have the flexibility to alter local property and other tax rates to raise revenues to cover loans. Nine countries: Australia, Bhutan, Fiji, India, Indonesia, Iran, Japan, Kiribati, and Vanuatu scored 3 points.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1fd30d3d-759d-4adc-9c7b-5277676a309d": {"__data__": {"id_": "1fd30d3d-759d-4adc-9c7b-5277676a309d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/city-enabling-environment-rating", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "City Enabling Environment Rating", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/city-enabling-environment-rating", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "986fb577f42816c3b428bba3b442b672f5556db282265c6c95dd55a2946a2902"}, "2": {"node_id": "8528f2f8-dad0-4774-855b-7b37632fca8d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/city-enabling-environment-rating", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "70ebb26eed0390934ff0bb2335cac33ecee5a0f38b8d6eefaf5337ada21f51a1"}}, "hash": "3828eeae37330c88ee19e3189a2f62d2588ea5272aaedfc3951da78f