"Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "City Enabling Environment Rating", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/city-enabling-environment-rating", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6c64f4386a44ee4908b9e42d34a39ac7767133fd5463518aba958e309db94fbf"}}, "hash": "6c64f4386a44ee4908b9e42d34a39ac7767133fd5463518aba958e309db94fbf", "text": "the end of January 2017.26 The definition of each local government category is defined by the Local Autonomy Law endorsed in 1947 based on the Articles 92, Chapter 8 of the Constitution of Japan. Local government legislations correspond to each other and are in line with the Constitution; they provide guidance for local government responsibilities and authority. Article 93 of the Constitution provides for the establishment of local councils as the legislative body, and defines the direct public election of members of local council and the heads of the executive branch of local government (governors and mayors). Details of powers and relations between local councils, governors and mayors are defined in the local autonomy law, and electoral procedures are defined by the public offices election law. In performing their functions, local governments have authority to manage some local taxes. Major local taxes are individual resident (inhabitant) tax, corporate resident (inhabitant) tax, local 26 Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications. (2016). White Paper on Local Public Finance, 2016 consumption tax, fixed assets tax, city planning tax, real estate acquisition tax and motor vehicle tax. Based on the principle of no taxation without law, basic tax affairs of local government are defined by the local tax law, which provides for the imposition and collection of taxes by local governments. The base of local taxes is defined by law; however, rates of tax are of three types; rates defined by the law, standard rates defined by the law where the local governments have discretion to change the rates within a certain range, and rates that local governments can decide. In addition to the local taxes defined by the local tax law, each local government can establish non-statutory (established by local ordinance, not by national law) local taxes. Establishment of non-statutory taxes by local governments needs consent of the Minister of Internal Affairs and Communications. The Minister shall give consent unless the proposed tax is unfair to taxpayers or has significant negative impact on the local economy.27 In relation to access to loans and financial markets, local governments with certain financial conditions (real debt service ratio (an index of the size of the redemption amount of debts (local bonds) and similar expenditure, and represents the cash-flow level) shall be under 18 per cent), local governments have discretion to issue local bonds by themselves (local government are required to notify the issuance of bonds to the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications). Article 2-14 of the local autonomy law prescribes that each local government shall, in performing its affairs, make best 27 Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications. (2016). White Paper on Local Public Finance, 2016\uff0dIllustrated\uff0d Rules and legal provisions on transparency in the running of local governments requiring regular, independent audits be conducted within specified timeframes exist and are applied. A clear national urban strategy exists, along with the financial and technical arrangements and capacities necessary to implement it. National legislation on citizen participation exists and is applied. Countries where city level action for environmental protection and promotion, including climate change and disaster risk reductio